I’ve typed this post up a number of times, always changing what/how I say things… probably most concerned about what you guys will think, but that’s okay. This is something that’s important to me, and if it can help one other person out there then this post has done it’s job.
I’m struggling. 2 years ago I moved from my home in the hills to the middle of the desert, away from my family and friends and all that I had known growing up. It has taught me so much already and I’ve been able to achieve some amazing things in this time, even checking things off my bucket list all while doing the thing I love. But I’m still struggling.

After West Coast Classic last year, the reality of what I had just done (moved to the desert by myself) had really set in. I lost my job around this time too, and I really think this is when I started feeling lost. But the next season came up before I knew it, and I was thrust back into competition mode. It was around this time that I lost my grandfather (G-dad) from a random heart attack. With the season starting though, I stayed in Vegas to train and mourn the loss alone. I competed at Granite Games finishing 4 points (one workout placement) away from accomplishing my dream, then had to withdraw from the Last Chance Qualifier when my body started to hurt and not work properly.
From this time on, I noticed that my anxiety was higher than normal… to a point of feeling paralyzed… what am I doing out here? Why am I doing this? I watched friends of mine accomplish the same goal that I had, feeling helpless and jealous, disappointed in my own results despite putting forth my full effort.
After a few months of down time, traveling around the world, and living an amazing life, my dad told me he was battling cancer again. I thought to myself why, why again, why right now? I stopped taking care of myself.. I would go days without eating or drinking hardly any water, my workouts became inconsistent, I would dread getting out of bed, and I hated the person I saw in the mirror. I felt weak and pathetic… my only job is to workout, and I couldn’t even do that. 

But today, we are actively making the choice to work on these things.
(Second post to come)

When I posted yesterday, the goal was not to try and get a bunch of sympathy & pity from everyone out there. My goal is to share how I feel and the steps I’m taking to grow. By doing so, I want to encourage others to know that it’s okay to not be okay. 

It’s okay to be sad, down, depressed, anxious, helpless, alone… whatever you’re feeling, it is okay. I promise you.

That’s always the toughest part of this journey for me… I’ve always felt like talking about it made me look weak and incapable, like there’s something wrong with me. 

But that’s what I’m learning anxiety wants you to think… and it’s in those times when you DON’T talk and you don’t process it that the snowball takes off down the hill and before I know it, I’ve spiraled out of control. 

So now, I’m taking the positive steps to help myself through these times..
I’m talking to a therapist, something I never thought I would do. I’m learning to practice more mindful activities, like long walks with Danner to help calm my mind, journaling my thoughts to help process them, and taking each day as it comes. 

I can’t do a damn thing to change how I ended up here… the reality is that all of my decisions and actions have lead me here. I can either continue down the road I’m on, or take the small steps - day after day, hour after hour, moment after moment - to become the person I believe I am. 

It’s not easy work and a lot of it comes to reframing my thoughts and beliefs, mainly the ones that I have about myself. It’s hard in any sport when your outcome becomes your identity… this is something else that I’ll elaborate on more in the future, but I think a lot of people struggle in knowing and believing TRULY in who they are. 

So again, my goal isn’t to get a bunch of messages and have all of you guys reach out (which I am extremely grateful for everyone who did). I want you to know that it’s okay, whatever worries you will pass, and that the most important thing is to not lose yourself in any of this… YOU are truly all you have at the end of the day. And YOU ARE F😀CKING AWESOME 🫶🏻🖤

One topic that’s been on my mind lately is remembering that my value is not found in my results. It is the effort, not the outcome, where we can quantify the things we can control… work ethic, attitude, discipline, doing the right things. The competition finish on the other hand, cannot be manhandled. 

My sixth CrossFit open is wrapping up and it’s going to be one of my worst finishes. I could try and complain about something, but I’ll take full responsibility for the position I put myself in. More than anything, this feels like a wake up call for me to take care of myself and my sh*t to make this dream a realty. 

One question that’s been on my mind lately is “Are you willing to sacrifice who you are, for what you will become?”

A whole list of habits, routines, comfort zones, or mindsets that have got me in the position I’m in. And to become what I truly believe I can be - my ‘best self’ if you will - then I have to change my habits, routines, and mindset going forward. 

While I am working on this daily, it can be tough to see where my results end up. Of course I’ve compared myself to every other competitor out there… of course I’m comparing myself to what I believe I’m capable of as well. But every day, I’m taking the steps to correct this and become the best competitor I can become. 

And what’s amazing is that everyone in my corner - in Las Vegas, West by God Virginia, Australia, all over the world - loves me and will always love me, regardless of how I finish. That’s pretty cool huh? I know lots of people on here know me as a CrossFit athlete, but obviously I am much more than that and hope I can be known for more than that. My message has always been be you and love you. You’re all you’ve got and you’re a really awesome person to have. Keep loving yourself and chasing those dreams kid 😴🫶🏻🖤

I’ve been lost.

Honestly, for the last two years of my life I’ve never felt like I had a very strong sense of who I was. Yes I could give you my elevator pitch to tell you all the things I’ve accomplished, or talk about my friends and family who I care about. But me… who am I? What gives me purpose? Am I valuable? Am I enough?

Through this process, I found myself allowing others to determine this for me… I placed my value in what others thought of me. I let their words, actions, and how they treated me determine my value. This could look like anything for me, but time and time again I found myself looking for worth in how I finished at competitions and my relationships with women. These two things dictated how I looked at myself everyday. I found myself in plenty of situations where I was looking for a woman to tell me how valuable I was, and if she couldn’t provide that, or wasn’t ready to, then I would be heartbroken. Why am I not enough for her?
One spot, 4 points, one different finish on a workout and I could be a Games athlete… Would people like me more if I was one? Would I like me more if I was one? 

But lately, I’ve realized that I’m f*ckin awesome. NOT in a way that’s self-centered, pretentious, or egotistical. But in the way that damn.. I LOVE MYSELF. I love who I am - faults, failures, and all. Yes I’ve came up short on all my goals so far. Yes I haven’t been able to find someone to share my life with. But that’s okay. I love the man I see in the mirror everyday now.
I love the man who has the guts to chase a dream, leave his family to move to the desert, and make sacrifices daily for this dream. I love the man who has loved and lost, showed his authentic heart, and has learned every day through this process. I love the man who no longer looks for someone else to validate what he already thinks about himself. I love the man who has pulled himself up from the darkest times of his life and who is making this life the one he wants. I love that man. I love me.

I hope this can be another piece of the conversation that I’m sharing with you all through my journey. NOT so you can praise me anything, but so that you can see hey wow… I love myself too :)

Filling my cup with good people 🤲🏼🫶🏻🤘🏼

Over the last few days, I’ve been able to fill my cup through connecting with other amazing humans I have in my life. From my big bro graduating the police academy, to reconnecting with childhood friends, to being part of a community that’s making some huge impacts, I’ve felt so happy and at peace lately. 

The human connection is something that I’m really paying attention to lately.. I love connecting with people who stand for the same things I do, and all of these people are that. I’m forever grateful for the people who’s paths cross with mine, and leave me better once they’ve passed on. Thank you friends🖤🫶🏻

Also - THANK YOU @lskd for making this all possible. Without you, I wouldn’t be able to be doing what I love.

Also also if you get to the very end you can see me in my rare form ;)

As I’m sure most have understood by now, I’ve decided to step away from the competitive CrossFit season for this year. Coming into this year I felt very underprepared - which is no ones fault but my own. I neglected to take care of my mind and body, and it was affecting so many parts of my life. I’m lucky enough to be able to take a step back, refocus and rebuild things, and hopefully come back as the best version of myself as I can. Thank you to my family, friends, and sponsors who have showed their support and encouragement while I go through this process. I’m excited for the world to see the new version of Matt D. 

You will most definitely see me back on the competition floor again and you’ll want to be watching. Until then, I’m going to take a little walk in the desert. See you in 40 days🤘🏼

Here I am again - trying to find the right way to say how I’m feeling. 
I’ve been lucky enough to have a platform on social media to be able to share my thoughts/feelings, and that’s always been received with open arms. So first of all, I want to say thank you🙌🏼
Secondly, I want to say that when I share these thoughts, I want you to know I’m not looking for your pity. I don’t need you to feel sorry for me. I’m not a sob story. Instead, I share my thoughts so that if someone out there is going through a dark time and can relate to anything I’m saying, they can use my words or examples to help themselves grow.

The last 6 months of my life has no doubt been some of the hardest yet. I thought that when I signed off my social media a few weeks ago, it would be a relatively easy time for me.
I thought it would be a peaceful time for me to be working on myself - physically, mentally, and emotionally. I thought that by removing the distractions, my negative thoughts/feelings would also go away.

But if I’m being honest, that few weeks was some of the hardest time for me mentally.
And for the first time on this journey, I faced the reality of quitting.
I thought about being done with this pursuit.
I thought about hanging the shoes up and moving on with my life. 
I thought I was a failure.
I thought about all the people that told me I wasn’t good enough and that I wouldn’t make it.
I thought about the people who stopped believing in me.
And I started to believe them too.
Maybe that all was true.
Maybe I’m not good enough. 
Maybe this dream wasn’t meant for me.

And that’s when I realized the lesson of this past few months. Yes it was some of my hardest times, but what I’ve found along the way can’t be faked or fabricated. I found my purpose. I truly found out why I do what I do, and what I wanted to do with that purpose. I found that person inside of me that grabbed my hand and dragged me up out of the shit I was in. I found out how to do it by myself, for myself. 
I found myself.

Stop looking for someone else to help you. No one’s coming.
But I’ll leave you with this - What if you’re the answer you’ve been praying for? What if you are the one you’ve been waiting for?

Haven’t been sharing a lot on here lately, but the thoughts have still been flowing✍🏼
Admittedly, I’ve struggled with knowing what to share on my Instagram. A lot of you know me from competing in CrossFit and without that at the moment, I’ve wondered if you guys would still care to see about my life and hear from me. I found myself wondering what people would think if I’m showing more of my life and myself. But I realize now that there’s not enough time to care about that. It’s not worth the energy to care what others think of you.

I’d love to hear if there’s anything you’d like to see more of from me, but if not - hope you enjoy the ride📸🤗🤘🏼🧿
There’s no “right time” to talk about your mental health, but often it seems like we wait until it’s too late. Please don’t wait🫶🏻🖤

Courage is knowing something might hurt, but doing it anyways. 
Strength is continuing to be vulnerable, despite being hurt in the past.
Boys (& girls).. please don’t close yourself off and bottle your emotions until it’s too late. I know you may have been told it’s wrong for you to feel that way, but the reality is that there’s nothing wrong with you for feeling the way you feel. Everyone is going through something, but no one has to go through it alone. 
Men - let’s talk about it. Check in on your boys. Give them a call. You never know how much that person may be looking for someone to care about them. And if you need to talk about it… Be courageous. Be strong. Be brave. 

Just please don’t wait🫶🏻🖤

If you’d like, please go watch the documentary at the link in my bio and share the message. Love you all🤟🏼

“A smooth sea never made a skilled sailor”

I think that one of the unique parts of the human experience is our ability to use our mind to explore and understand the different feelings and thoughts we have. 

Journaling and quiet, meditative time have been two of my tools for exploring my thoughts. By writing my thoughts down, I’m able to verbalize feelings, put them in comprehensible (or sometimes not hahah) statements, and explore where they came from. Writing things down helps me to find clarity in those uncertain times, and it helps me to simplify things. Often after I’m done journalling, I’ll realize that all of the anxiety, which has turned into a giant snowball, started as no more than a snowflake..
Spending quiet time alone (or with the pup) gives me even more time to sift through all my thoughts, calm myself down from the impending avalanche of my anxiety, and redirect my thoughts towards something positive and constructive. That time is also set for me to allow gratitude into my life.. celebrating all of my “wings” for the day.

West ‘By God’ Virginia
